	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2982086605" id="dsq-comment-2982086605">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2982086605">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-11-03</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2982086605" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2982086605" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Yo Daan!</p><p>1) Performance can be an issue with forms... but only once you have *many* (e.g. 50, 100 or more) fields in your form. Just check out your web debug toolbar's "Performance" tab if you'd like: you can see if a page is slowing down that has a form. So, it's definitely possible... but probably not an issue.</p><p>2) Yep, this is a really good question! So usually, the "thing" that you're selecting is a list that lives in a database somewhere. That means that - other than the fact that having 1000 options on your page is horrible UI (and slow to load) - the EntityType is the perfect solution. And the EntityType really gives you *two* things: (A) it renders as a select element with all of your entities as options and (B) [much more importantly] when the id of the selected entity is submitted (e.g. 5) the EntityType queries for this and converts it into that object (e.g. Genus) before setting it back on your object.</p><p>What we want is that *second* functionality (B) but with a field that renders as a hidden field. The setup would look like this:</p><p>i) Field renders as an <code>&lt;input type="hidden" value="5" /&gt;<br>ii) You build some jQuery magic auto-complete magic, completely independent of the form system (except that it should read the "5" as the default value, and when you select the a new option, it should override the value with the id of the newly selected option).<br>iii) When you submit the id, you would want the (B) functionality above to convert the id (e.g. 5) back into your entity.<br><br>Unfortunately, this type of "HiddenEntityId" field doesn't exist in Symfony (though it's been proposed). But, you can add a custom field pretty easily - here's a bundle that has one (you can use this or use it as inspiration): https://github.com/Glifery/EntityHiddenTypeBundle and here's another example: https://gist.github.com/bjo3rnf/4061232. We *do* use this here on KnpU, it's really handy.<br><br>Let me know if that makes sense!<br><br>Cheers!</code></p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2980647659" id="dsq-comment-2980647659">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
